The solution is from:

https://leetcode.com/problems/rotate-image/discuss/18895/Clear-Java-solution

The basic idea is:

1. Separate the matrix to multiple cycles, go through the cycles from outer to inner
2. For each cycle (with 4 arrays connected), go through the top array
3. For each elements of the array, calculate the new position and move the value. Note that for each element, we need to move the value for 4 times (for the 4 arrays).

The code:

```
class Solution {
    public void rotate(int[][] matrix) {
        if(matrix == null || matrix.length == 0 || matrix[0].length == 0)return;
        int n = matrix.length;
        for(int i = 0;i < n / 2;i++) {
            for(int j = i;j < n - i - 1;j++) {
                int tmp = matrix[i][j];
                matrix[i][j] = matrix[n - j - 1][i];
                matrix[n - j - 1][i] = matrix[n - i - 1][n - j - 1];
                matrix[n - i - 1][n - j - 1] = matrix[j][n - i - 1];
                matrix[j][n - i - 1] = tmp;
            }
        }
    }
}
```

Some explanations:

1. Why do we use (n / 2) as the count of i?

i means the count of all the cycles. Since the length of the matrix is n, obviously we have (n / 2) cycles.

2. Why do we use i and (n - i - 1) as the range of j?

j means the count of the elements of the top array of current cycle. Since the cycle becomes smaller and smaller according to the increasing of i, the start of j is i. Since the cycle is always symmetrical, the end of j is (n - i - 1). Note that we use  (n - i - 1) but not (n - i) because we need to ignore the latest one of each line (which should be handled as first one in next loop).

3. How to understand the calculation of the positions in the inner loop?

Since the cycle is always symmetrical, the rule is:

For any assignment expression, the positions A[x1][y1] and B[x2][y2] between the "=" operator must be:

1. **x1 == y2**
2. **y1 and x2 are symmetrical**

e.g.

```
matrix[i][j] = matrix[n - j - 1][i];
```

Both x1 and y2 are equal (i), and y1(j) and x2(n - j - 1) are symmetrical. The same for other assignments.

