## Explanation:

### Solution 01

- Here we took 4pointers: ***row start(rs), row end(re), column start(cs), column end(ce).***
- Every time while loop runs, it takes the outer border elements to their fixed position.
- Then we move to inner borders.
- **Time complexity:** O(n^2).

### Solution 02

- This solution is more simple than the previous one.
- Here we transpose the matrix, it will make every row element to column element.
- Then we simply reverse every row.
- **Time complexity:** O(n^2).

---

## Code:

```cpp
//Solution 01:
****class Solution {
public:
    void rotate(vector<vector<int>>& matrix) {
        int n= matrix.size();
        int rs=0, re=n-1, cs=0, ce=n-1, i ,j;
        while(rs<re && cs<ce){
            for(i=cs; i<ce; i++){
                swap(matrix[rs][i],matrix[i][ce]);
            }
            for(i=re; i>rs; i--){
                swap(matrix[ce][i],matrix[i][cs]);
            }
            for(i=cs,j=ce; i<ce,j>cs; i++,j--){
                swap(matrix[rs][i], matrix[re][j]);
            }
            rs++; re--; cs++; ce--;
        }
    }
};

