solutions.content:
The observation is that after a 90 degree rotation, the number from row `r` and column `c` will end up in row `c` and column `n-1-r`. Also rotating the matrix 4 times will result the number to end up in the original place, so the positions create cycles of size 4. Thus, if there is a cycle `a -> b -> c -> d -> a`, in Golang we can swap these values in one line like so `a, b, c, d = b, c, d, a`. 

Also we need to make sure we rotate every cycle exactly once, so we need to start rotating the cycles from the upper left quarter of the matrix. If `n` is odd, we need to be careful to skip either middle column or middle row.

```
func rotate(matrix [][]int)  {
    n := len(matrix)
    for r := 0; r < n/2; r++ {
        for c := 0; c < (n+1)/2; c++ {
            matrix[r][c], matrix[c][n-1-r], matrix[n-1-r][n-1-c], matrix[n-1-c][r] = 
                matrix[n-1-c][r], matrix[r][c], matrix[c][n-1-r], matrix[n-1-r][n-1-c]
        }
    }
}
```

